To ensure that the CDs are converted to GMA-CDs, FTIR and 1H NMR were done on both CDs and GMA-CDs (Fig. 2
                        ). For the FTIR analyses for both compounds, there are characteristics peaks at 3600–3200 cm−1 (OH and NH stretching), 1515 cm−1 (NH bending of amide groups) and 1500–600 cm−1 (long chain bands, CN and CO stretching). There are few peaks that are unique to themselves. A peak at 1664 cm−1 can be spotted at spectrum of CDs which corresponds to the CO stretching of amides. Another peak at 1540 cm−1 (NH bending of amine group) is also only available in the CDs spectrum. These are evident as CDs are synthesized from degummed silk, which contains proteins, and amines/amides are present. However, both peaks disappear from the GMA-CDs spectrum, and a new peak at 1713 cm−1 appears. This new peak observed corresponds to the CO stretching of α,β-unsaturated ester. It is also observed that the intensity of the peak at 1585 cm−1 (CC stretching) increases significantly. As the amine group reacts with the epoxide group of the GMA, the amine peak at 1540 cm−1 disappears. As the amide groups are more shielded in the core, the signal might be weaker and was engulfed by the less shielded α,β-unsaturated ester. Hence, indicating that GMA modification is successful. From the NMR spectra, it is even more apparent that the modification is successful, with an additional of a peak at 6.1 ppm (OCHOC=O) and 5.7 ppm (C=CH
                        2).
